### Key design points
- **True sliding window**: each request triggers `evictExpired`, which trims timestamps relative to the *current* time — the window boundary moves continuously, with no periodic counter reset.
- **O(expired) eviction**: timestamps arrive in monotonic order, so the array stays sorted and we only splice the aged-out prefix.
- **`Retry-After` / `X-RateLimit-Reset`** are computed from the oldest in-window timestamp, i.e. exactly when the next slot frees up.
- **Memory safety**: the periodic sweep deletes idle IP buckets; `close()` clears the interval (and `unref()` keeps it from blocking process exit on its own).

One note for very high throughput: this is in-memory and per-process. If you run multiple Node workers/instances, each has its own limit — back it with a shared store (e.g. Redis sorted sets via `ZREMRANGEBYSCORE` + `ZCARD`) for a cluster-wide sliding window. I kept this single-process per the spec.

